(319, 228, '', '<p><strong>&nbsp;My invention has 2 parts: the refreshable braille display, and the character detection.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>PART 1&nbsp;&mdash;&nbsp;THE DISPLAY:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Braille is a language that uses raised dots to create letters. Each letter is formed with a maximum of 6 dots; each character is called a braille cell. There are two forms of braille writing: uncontracted braille and contracted braille. I chose to focus on uncontracted braille, as the other version is mostly reserved for experienced users and the rules may take many years for me to learn.&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>A refreshable braille display is an electronic form of braille that is usually made of one row of braille cells. The machine can automatically raise and lower dots to create different characters when it receives input.&nbsp;</strong><strong>The question I need to research is - how can one control hundreds of tiny machines effectively?&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Prototype design Iteration #1</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>My initial idea was to create a handheld device, a sort of glove, that a visually impaired person could use to read when they wore it. Here is one of my first sketches:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><img src=\"https://lh4.googleusercontent.com/4gXdSlzoc9Nao3dFOi3KFAfn-CZjzZ8MM0UBFzo-mjEv7t5luO_EqZmwUBC9BRAXck_OZusqKCX9m_ZEKuuM17_VWgZk9m_Fwr2uRA4pjE9DdOiuSg6kQdy_FgbSug\" style=\"height:236px; width:431px\" /></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;As I was working on my prototype design, I realized that it would not be the best choice. I had emailed several visual impairment specialists and therapists and found that a big source of frustration for the visually impaired was the fact that most commercially available displays could only show one line of text at a time.&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Creating a multi-line braille display would be a good trade-off for creating a single-line display. Even though it provides for a more portable device, the invention would not be very easy to use, which is one of my criteria. In addition to being portable, the device would be useable for the visually impaired.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Prototype design iteration #2</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>I began by exploring low-cost, thin, refreshable braille displays and discovered that most commercially available braille displays use the piezo effect for moving dots. However, this method is not favorable. The smallest braille displays are quite large, often weighing over one pound.&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Prototype design Iteration #3</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>I wanted to find a better system than the one currently used, so I began to research miniature actuators. I narrowed it down to the following list:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p><strong>Miniature motors</strong></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p><strong>Dielectric elastomer</strong></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p><strong>Pneumatic</strong></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>However, these alone would not be able to solve the problem that I have. One braille cell is only a few millimeters in length,&nbsp; &nbsp; as they are designed to fit on a fingertip.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Cons of existing actuators:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p><strong>Miniature motors (High Cost)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li>\r\n		<p><strong>I had previously heard that miniature motors are used in cell phone cameras to help stabilize the lens. However, after doing some research, I realized that they were extremely expensive.</strong></p>\r\n		</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p><strong>Dielectric elastomer (Low energy efficiency)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li>\r\n		<p><strong>A dielectric elastomer is a special piece of rubber (neoprene or nitrile) covered in carbon-conductive grease which expands when voltage is passed through.</strong></p>\r\n		</li>\r\n		<li>\r\n		<p><strong>I first began to research this idea, as it seemed to be the most promising. I looked through youtube videos and research papers to find out how this can be done. I created a diagram of a braille dot expanding (shown below) However, I couldn&rsquo;t find any real information. So, I decided to experiment with the formulas for elastomers and discovered that even a small change in the rubber requires several kilowatts of power.<img src=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/5WDHlshj8Xo5XsXZ6_wDGxsHPNiFhlWatkSvtiQW0wsQJkc6CT6JjitNuVpEeDwEVnhqLGyRcFnsSRrvmEkad6yVpfNNHX_rXuqjLPs-yAeOAJoBaX8jj6EbJjCluQ\" style=\"height:172px; width:477px\" /></strong></p>\r\n		</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p><strong>Pneumatic (Complex design)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li>\r\n		<p><strong>A refreshable braille display for four cells was created using pneumatic actuators by the University of Michigan. I did a little bit of research into their project and discovered that pneumatic actuators overcomplicated the design, as many other components would be needed.</strong></p>\r\n		</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p><strong>Ferrofluid Actuator (Inefficient, unstable)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li>\r\n		<p><strong>I also explored the idea of creating a grid of copper wires which would raise and lower dots with a specific fluid between the wires. Voltage would be sent through a certain row and column in the grid, which would make the fluid clump together, creating a bulge. I would pass the exact amount of voltage through each wire so that one current would have no effect, while two currents make it clump together. Here is a diagram that I created, showing fluid packed into one braille cell.</strong></p>\r\n		</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><img src=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/X6oNCSIDP4eJjnCGEPZLi_5v8ghpxM96oLwgDV1HQdUebO32HHFlaIIgdCCXsQSXJMQIDDzP_oJ6eMeMQg9aUiQIfmQtWPYv3Th1jYMZAC6wFiUUVh9JXfmTEgPsPA\" style=\"height:138px; width:266px\" /></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>At the time, I was interested in exploring a certain fluid known as ferrofluid. Ferrofluid&rsquo;s property is that it is attracted to metal objects. However, after researching more, I realized that this method would not work, as ferrofluid cannot be easily de-activated.&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Prototype design Iteration#4 - PDMS (time-consuming, large, and difficult)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>However, this research gave me a new idea. I had read about a method of moving objects called soft robotics; robots that mimic living things such as humans, plants, or animals. This led me to start looking into microfluidics, which uses the properties of fluids to manufacture miniature devices.&nbsp; I began to research how microfluidics devices are made.&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>I started by looking into PDMS, which is a plastic-like material that shrinks when heated. This is useful in microfluidics because channels can be etched into the material and shrunk to miniaturize the size of a circuit. My design used the principles of a tesla valve combined with the organization of the copper wire grid. A tesla valve is a pipe with small notches that restrict the free flowage of water. Below is a design of what I wanted to create, showing one row of braille dots. Working similarly to the copper wire grid idea, I would generate a force on one end of the pipe. The fluid would then flow through the tube,&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><img src=\"https://lh4.googleusercontent.com/m3tZ3Q2GepJbSvhFy3VRmCx7_O8ikDtRp-qDn9rtut4Anikg0-4prLOLc1aV2D_9V76L1uhvEeAF-7LvCM1i7TDbRs2BqO6oT85ovVr0VY0qOZ-IxLSc9yN9TvtDQA\" style=\"height:192px; width:375px\" /></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>I experimented with this for a little while (I created channels made of baked styrofoam, as it is made similarly to PDMS), but I soon realized that this method would be time-consuming, large, and difficult. The cuts I made in the styrofoam came out too small when baked. Below are the results.<img src=\"https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/v31jEeNBjvUnZMHyIvGKwogLdf3-GfwM4VgD3SrLRYsvh27zosrqaOL2gyuCyvEnviNzACgLs0sK4MoRPKzKH5dByUCDJxCwWB8MlgQUFq3L15QH9lbH2G5cFQSZNQ\" style=\"height:285px; width:242px\" /><img src=\"https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/19UH81Pnz22NcBPy6ufuHuUA-tEQSOyYlZJX3S1qx7dJoA1mjurEGfMOCc-DcmL6F_W1g3kBLlOg_D_Q2Y0Zd05kT81QrPCbhJtqSeUznv0te4Nn-WcWoIIdWrh6ag\" style=\"height:284px; width:257px\" /></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Prototype design Iteration #5 (LDPE)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>I then slightly changed my approach and attempted to use small flexible plastic tubes, instead of solidified ones. I began to create tubes with soft and flexible plastic (low-density polyethylene (LDPE)); sealed with a hot iron. One of the major issues with hydraulic mechanisms is leaks; something I experienced firsthand. Firstly, the iron is extremely hot and melts the plastic if it comes in direct contact. To fix this problem, I partially covered the plastic with aluminum foil. Secondly, filling the tube with water was very difficult to perform manually, so I needed to purchase syringes. Here are some pictures of my work and materials(I made a lot of attempts).&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>The tubes I displayed on the cardboard are some of my successful attempts.&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>I learned many things about how the tubes should be made:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p><strong>Cutting a larger frame than needed initially</strong></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p><strong>Water-filled tubes cannot be sealed shut easily, but they can be heated vertically to minimize the risk of leaks</strong></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p><strong>It is best to trace out the boundaries of the tube</strong></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p><strong>All edges need to be sealed twice (especially if the tube is filled)</strong></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><img src=\"https://lh4.googleusercontent.com/uKaSBRBUrfNpo4V3MdDIC6h1o9n_0goTHNsctxwDdbUidR1fcLyBae_CizWen5frgX7ST3O8hSvkmp6gIATh7cdJy_F9UFilvgBm4UuK2FE0I9WP0wHGD69UnK_zOA\" style=\"height:322px; width:241px\" /><img src=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/xYK3uhs5uk5REUQGuukB_3caK6NZ-PAjmK0GD2Tx4Oomj--Xtjh6VsKYH_-VZ5tpR8tUmIfg_31kbA75tT2yengcQv7bBSuhSDTJJlqbUzVzd8VA7hP_fDjZH8zCSQ\" style=\"height:320px; width:241px\" /><img src=\"https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/1zVYYxO5CMBxKGQk90WZ71MaX8RrtkECW5sXJHJ1ajKpqUiAwrr11BGHzGfiXzDNr8WwA4JJDFRni2r-gBtiC5gK8exO8iEISCpLKcSa5JPj4YjTxrZaz9aiVcaeuw\" style=\"height:278px; width:208px\" /><img src=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/i8LT64qjr1lxXuXzCg_f-ItoSfhqtrypqLVpHuwVxLUTNfd1d9ExJOIzpULaXKCzhE7_GQZrP4J7UXNI5fKoCo7ErCjlnxVBmZeo9O9r-nQY_G2MgaLb_6iG-iu1JQ\" style=\"height:277px; width:207px\" /><img src=\"https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/Hl0JlWQ8pa2nxR8ag5EBvCyljAdx-eQgS_oWVWrq64nDcxXFWZzntx_Y8QpmfM3ic9EOfW7LRy0wdhBpubQqwSV550CqB_fYVGqZ4H6_1_jUsPsi7KS9_mg__iIaqA\" style=\"height:276px; width:207px\" /><img src=\"https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/KlpGk_A6ytnzdsK70-Vr4zTNgQoEtkfUjC_F91TK1oJ0UI-bgLLzPSTUTzWQkpBndSVZIbqGQGUnuJQubMMz787dDAhwlAjjrpjh5oOXCzEfeErAAappRMx3iTtlYA\" style=\"height:278px; width:207px\" /></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>At the same time, I was researching a method of actuation, as a simple tube cannot move. I decided to use solenoids, as they were an actuator I had previously read about. Solenoids use a conductive coil to turn electrical energy into a magnetic field, giving it the capability to move parts. My main problem was that commercially available solenoids were too large for the scale of my project. I realized that if I created one of my own, I could miniaturize my product on a significant scale. I purchased some magnet wire and began to experiment. Building a working electromagnet is dependent on the number of coils, the number of coil overlaps, and the core material. I soon realized that creating these without a solenoid winder would be very difficult. I changed the core material and the amount of voltage applied with each iteration, but the electromagnet still wouldn&rsquo;t produce a magnetic field. Below is an image of my initial planning and attempts. I noticed that changing the gauge of the wire is ineffective, as the thinner the wire, the more likely there are overlaps.&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><img src=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/i0iJsHwlWlsIaqCS_6-B5oY3VWMStKr1O7wrT28SZFl_nC-5kL6ytldR80OzsUNC5SJDzXMAdeQ2isYip49U7EB3NUNcRQCL_zCuk6Wn9ZRPcJW83T62UFI_Q74kLQ\" style=\"height:207px; width:281px\" /></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>After doing a lot of research, I came across the use of an electromagnet for the rudder/aileron for a remote-controlled airplane. Here is an image (not mine) of one of the existing designs. This model can be constructed at only a few millimeters in diameter, using small neodymium magnets to provide actuation.&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://www.instructables.com/Micro-Magnetic-Actuator-for-RudderAileron-Control/\">https://www.instructables.com/Micro-Magnetic-Actuator-for-RudderAileron-Control/</a><img src=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/8YpllsKfhbUMuBpO93QVQxNaNoWphV8Ry2_f1Io8RRoO27xFazynEGfuEVpeEpr1mxHZ46avKw6h99e2PcqGG4gydj00wPqZRUz9GZsfkO2vYtvsElQUU_5O804GGA\" style=\"height:206px; width:349px\" /></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>I attempted to make this at home but found it difficult due to the small size. I wish to come back to this in my next iterations. For my next tests, I used small pre-built commercially available solenoids.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Now that I had collected the individual parts of my actuator, I started to come up with designs of how they could work together. I was interested in minimizing the amount of material needed, so I came up with a design similar to my previous iterations: the copper wire grid and tesla valve. When two forces were applied to a certain point in the grid, it would expand. Below is a diagram showing one braille cell. However, I soon realized that this would not work. As shown in examples 1 and 2 (labeled Ex:1 and Ex:2), any diagonally actuated cells will fail, as the adjacent cells will actuate in the process.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;<img src=\"https://lh4.googleusercontent.com/tncbdw6VhZb7WuGAwn0HuOQDSQBeNxFKMHBGizUgmiy3XP_skofKDqg85zCKuLcIXFGgG8bmKW_24YNv6dhQmdgvgoL8goyYMn0jI1sBose2yFi4QXKivUBx9_oWVg\" style=\"height:281px; width:457px\" /></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>I also researched the three-way actuator valve, something commonly used in household faucets. The valve can allow water to flow in two directions; it can control the two directions separately, or actuate them together. However, after receiving feedback from Professor Muhammad Ahmed from EMU, I decided to abandon this idea.&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Since I had established that the dots cannot be controlled together, I decided to come up with some designs on how the electromagnet can actuate the tubes. Below is one of my earlier designs (labeled).</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><img src=\"https://lh4.googleusercontent.com/2YTrAyEZNjkHlDUMzIqfb8KdLmELzEA76XFAGoCQto4R341qjl3ByfhcmFux6J_1M27vE0fvrcRJtyh7Bg1CfrQvKIjMipZeMDKgw7fhUEwdphbH07SOjfgHEmtAwA\" style=\"height:316px; width:581px\" /></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p><strong>When power is given to the electromagnet (6) it develops a magnetic field, making it attracted to the magnetic polymer/metal.&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p><strong>Since the electromagnet is placed above the tube (4), it compresses it, causing the water inside to flow up the tube, filling up the loose/weak spot (5).</strong></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p><strong>This spot then bulges through the holes in the braille frame (1).&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>I tried testing this with the materials I had, however, it did not work as expected. Due to the irregularities in the water-filled tubes I constructed, the water wouldn&rsquo;t create enough of a bulge. I then began experimenting with the tubes to see what kind of pressure and what location would produce the desired result. Soon, I found that if the tube is pinched or bent in a certain spot, the tube will begin to lift upwards. This effect can become stronger if more bends are made to the tube, if the horizontal section is larger than the vertical section, and if a less viscous fluid is used (glycerin).&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>After researching fluid dynamics, I found out that this is due to the Venturi effect, which says that a constricted area of the pipe increases the speed of the fluid passing through.&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Below is a video of the actuation from one of the trials I conducted. I am applying only a small amount of force to the tube.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><img src=\"https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/9b6QxVItkLmT82msakEVO1u30259lBkVRh0TEX0QQj3ECQHajZw6-AbkkvUk7gN5syLDGMDlHchBbHgvBGpQEt7PN4gxwXTaCGOWsCWeZXSGwKbDt7qqxes8itNJbg\" style=\"height:282px; width:499px\" /></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n<strong>My next big issue was how the actuators should be arranged in the refreshable braille display. At first, it may seem like the easiest way to place them would be as shown in figure 1. However, an issue occurs when you begin to add more cells (figure 2). I wasn&rsquo;t able to easily access the middle two dots.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><img src=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/42AQQHZJeEMgijCptrH0WllRFnQlggveWxZXsGw3ERYc90DgqPF6GYng3bz4iDF_aizMSWdcM5LbPx3s1393UkwQKf9kaxP0hK_JTmfOsl-ODodffwXrlJDiJAyElQ\" style=\"height:347px; width:251px\" /><img src=\"https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/IYEAbFVvG0I0o8jEvlh9V0HHwhwE6Coca1HIzM7xVtiVNDkeRYMNuDBYwnCAIWY3uGrhSFenJEkCLTtWPxr97H70iUcgEhArLb9Gs66Ep1QdgiYt6oNkgfG3KK-JIw\" style=\"height:349px; width:541px\" /></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Previously, I kept a flat, unyielding surface behind the tube, which somewhat pinched it. After experimenting a little, I realized that a small sheet of paper/plastic could accomplish the same task. Below is a drawing of the design. The blue part is the tube, and behind it is a sheet of paper. This knowledge would help me design the layout.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><img src=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/PWsbPmHa2FHtPTmQg4AWlaPOntaGOWtNDqVR9g1ZisgDp9mO8RN7Yubi6aPBKejWTxkBZ5Ezw3e7vk8SGMy78IWrUOfE-O-XGKFoT_MlA3Za_SZ2418zmKDfxsePoQ\" style=\"height:127px; width:207px\" /></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>I then came up with another solution; reorienting a few parts. The green parts represent solenoids, the blue parts represent tubes, and the black parts on the tubes&rsquo; ends represent the supporting paper/plastic. My method allows the cells to be easily aligned next to each other, as shown on the following page.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>.<img src=\"https://lh4.googleusercontent.com/hP1eK6gMSmmUWR5s6ltA9-E_WHMxIc27uSpTGeT-Au2A6LDtlPRqWdu117AXb7oWHtifkBXWlgDAaQnQgpFhIj5jNCqwNWva0kmlx5M9YpTMkYBrh7hCrNZfmr-YoQ\" style=\"height:249px; width:155px\" /></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><img src=\"https://lh4.googleusercontent.com/7VsgJM9yL1e8OOEdBnO7VTHTq78lRShFEjllzTrKeiohJvEadzWSScH9Cf__qux3uLsRjxh9erVmzjHk4U1ZfID_xd36Dj6Ek-ZPYhVYF14CYg2jV2NeSr2uJu6NGQ\" style=\"height:286px; width:398px\" /></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n<strong>Prototype design Iteration #6</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;I drew out my layout on pieces of cardboard and experimented with some miniature pre-built solenoids that I purchased. I wanted to make only one braille cell, as a proof of concept for this prototype. Below are some images of my progress. I created small barriers out of cardboard to prevent the solenoids from slipping out of their positions, as the wires were extremely inflexible.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;<img src=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/01QwtxtXVuGuSsGpFo1EMBGcrsOxWYnNxoWmDViZqgafAUHUzxgQRkCPhTtXQ2RoIuhKvIztWkdbCsI27KNqmui6SIXm4gKY4NphW0COqAnV_2kYEEhLp6M2kEbY_g\" style=\"height:189px; width:408px\" /><img src=\"https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/ZPzuMB8Bmbl9U7bYPC4RTPmqerZ2xQaJqc5ihiABtilL-c-Jd2M5QXiBuHM_72Dw4f5gNLVK01qPLJ__QHPczJ1exywyWmkgOasp0lv5ZQ2NNcNJyQDoGw69VysjiA\" style=\"height:205px; width:384px\" /></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp; PART 2 &mdash;&nbsp;THE READER:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Now that I had created a display concept, I started work on the reader part, as the machine needed to receive input from somewhere. I planned to create a reader that can scan the text from an image using a camera. I decided to purchase a raspberry pi camera. I started looking into ways that I could read text off of an image.&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>I came up with a list of tasks that I needed to accomplish:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p><strong>Take a picture</strong></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p><strong>extract text from the image</strong></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p><strong>convert characters into voltage signals</strong></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p><strong>In the beginning, I was planning on extracting images from a video stream, as that would be easier to use. I used Thonny Python (already built into my raspberry pi) to turn on a video stream and capture the recording in a file. However, after viewing the clip, I noticed that it was not clear at all, as the camera wouldn&rsquo;t focus. I researched different ways to do it, and I came across video straightening methods called OIS (which stands for Optical Image Stabilization). This uses tiny mechanical parts to compensate for rapid movements in the film. However, these are slightly expensive and may be hard to create. In the future, I may come back to stabilization methods, however, I chose to use timed camera photos of the text.</strong></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p><strong>There are many ways to extract text from an image. One of the ideas I explored is pattern matching, where an image would be divided into sections, and each section would be compared to characters to see if they match. However, this method had some problems, as it would only work for a predetermined font and font size. However, I also read about ANN (artificial neural network) character recognition which uses machine learning to detect characters. I also found that there was a pre-built python package for character detection called Tesseract. After using the Linux command line to download Tesseract on my Raspberry Pi, I wrote code for reading text and gathering the first letter in the sentence (as my display prototype only holds one character)&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p><strong>I then wrote separate code that takes in a character as a parameter and checks it with several if statements. I then used the raspberry pi GPIO pin package to send voltage signals to each solenoid correspondingly</strong></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p><strong>Below is my coding flowchart</strong></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><img src=\"https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/9vDZWtGVR-43LCSmmaGqhGL-xVLnJM15s7rwQPacJT-eE9_1G1jX7-trrIAE93Rv6eBMuNprSJ8GZI9ecChb7REYdYD-dx_EbASbtWjFn5O-9g2yNq4zu07Co-c38A\" style=\"height:409px; width:725px\" /></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>I then began to work on the electrical aspect; how I would connect it all together. I knew that each solenoid needed to be controlled individually, so I began to research different ways I could modulate the amount of power flowing into each solenoid. I came up with two different solutions:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p><strong>Voltage regulator</strong></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p><strong>Potentiometers</strong></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p><strong>Relay switch</strong></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>A voltage regulator works by automatically reducing the power flowing into a certain part of a circuit. However, the voltage regulator had a set value and could not be opened and closed like a valve, so I discarded the idea.&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>I then began to look into potentiometers, or variable resistors. These looked good at first, but I realized that there were two types of potentiometers; digital potentiometers and mechanical potentiometers. I couldn&rsquo;t figure out how to operate digital potentiometers, so I moved on. At some point, I may come back to this idea.&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>This left only the relay switch. The relay switch uses specially curved electromagnetic coils to modulate the voltage. I decided to buy an 8-channel relay switch. Before hooking it up,&nbsp; I created a wiring diagram (shown below).</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><img src=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/5kadts_Xg-tVKSfybHRh5Fe_V-cEkQ6qQZ7CsCjNy1JU8FxEkM-iSSECCBK10BKT-EJ6FgNWCuAaFoly_CwvUN7GqJYoasoIYOCCRKSWaXP4Ro8Ambeio08vsuRf1Q\" style=\"height:279px; width:555px\" /></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;Here are some pictures of my attempts:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>8-channel relay switch</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><img src=\"https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/q1HBpdpWgs2C68uOegXxvFVmaNdk3x5ssRWF5tiA_yQzoXP3Jb7eTmtFzVuQeylROF4Y7FGKZfkNxUvn3hSqoqjVhvR3J5h7OYXRNyoGd7mMXlyaT_kWtiAk05NaEg\" style=\"height:290px; width:318px\" /><img src=\"https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/uOEq8oKsCwPBRrfEmPBhpxf-iS-LKhKv-2u9qX-ouvekldunQUy51duhUgExMhYk96epzxPBX_CQfQ_OWAOZGur6yeSUySAdbZq9Qhwg_xzYIMjdoKtN3MMK0xE5Iw\" style=\"height:286px; width:383px\" /></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n ', '2022-02-19 07:08:35'),
(331, 229, '', '<p>This machine has a 4 step process. The first thing that the user does is throw everything they have into the machine but do not throw in plastic bags. After that, step one(prototype 1) starts happening. Step one is where all the stuff you have thrown into will be sorted into two groups. Group one is plastic, metal, and glass i.e. the recyclables, and group two is anything else. Each step will be explained in detail after this paragraph. Step two(prototype 2) is when everything in group 1 is sent to a washer that will clean it. After everything is cleaned it moves on to step 3 which is it gets sorted again. This time it sorts metal, plastic, and glass into separate groups. Each of these groups except glass will be sent to step 4. The glass will be sent to a normal trash can. The plastics and the metals will be sent to step 4 which is a compactor that will compact all the plastics and the metals until they are emptied.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Step 1 will first allow 2-3 pieces of trash to be lowered onto a conveyor belt. On the conveyor belt, there will be a camera using R-FCN(Region-based Fully Convolutional Network) which is an object recognition algorithm to sense what the trash is. For this stage, it will sort between group 1(plastic, glass, metal) and everything else but it will use a 40% match rate to sort instead of the default 95%. This stage is mainly done to reduce the amount of trash getting into the washer. So a 40% match rate is done because object recognition software struggles to identify the object unless it is clean. So a 40% match rate will allow it to reduce the amount of trash in the cleaner and still have all of group 1 be sent to the washer.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Step 2 will have all of group 2(plastic, metal, glass) filling up inside it until it reaches 50% capacity. After that happens the cleaning cycle starts. The cycle starts with the 5 power washers spraying the plastic. They will have 4 on each side of the container and 1 on the top of the container. The pressure washers are all 500 psi and will be one for one minute. After one minute the inner container will spin for 30 seconds. This is done to dry the plastic as much as possible. After the spin is done then the bottom of the container will open and allow all the plastics to go.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Step 3 sorts group one into three separate groups which are plastic, glass, and metal. The sorting is done in the same format as step 1 but this time it is sorted between glass, metal, and glass. After this is done glass is sent to its trash can while metal and plastic are sent to step 4.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Step 4 is another cleaner. It works exactly the same as step 2 after that metal and plastic are sent to step 4. &nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Step 4 is a compactor. The compactor starts to compact after it reaches 75% capacity. After that happens it starts crushing the metal and the plastic from the top. This is done to reduce the number of times the trashman has to pick it up. If even after it is compacted and it&#39;s at 90% capacity then they will let the pickup crew know to come and get it.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This machine will be half underground to reduce the amount it intrudes above the ground. It will be lifted up using a hydraulic lift because of the weight of the machine.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The image below is only for the washing portion of the deisign. I am only focusing on the washing portion of the machine since this is a very big project.&nbsp;</p>\r\n ', '2022-02-20 03:13:55'),
