(319, 228, '<p><strong>There&rsquo;s just something special about the feel of a real book in your hands; nothing quite like the joy of laying with your feet up and reading that great page-turner you found at the library. Alas! The visually impaired face a real barrier in enjoying this experience.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>There are 33 million visually impaired people in the world, yet less than 1 % of published books are available in Braille. Furthermore, Braille books and assistive technology are expensive and inconvenient. This leaves a majority of printed books and reading material inaccessible for the visually impaired. This is the problem I am trying to solve.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>I became aware of this problem during the COVID lockdown period. Reading books was one of the things that got me through the long quarantine days. And that got me thinking about the kids who are visually impaired; what they might read and how they would spend their time. I then looked for the Braille section of my library and was dismayed to see just a few shelves with Braille books. That got me thinking more about this problem and I started to work on finding a solution for it.</strong></p>\r\n', '<p><strong>My goal is to make regular printed books (that are not Braille enabled) accessible to the visually impaired. And to achieve this goal, I want to invent a product that can recognize the text from a book and display it in Braille in the cheapest and most space-efficient way. Here is a set of criteria that my invention must fulfill.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<table>\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p><strong>Be cheap</strong></p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p><strong>Easy to use</strong></p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p><strong>Compatible with printed text and electronic devices</strong></p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p><strong>Portable</strong></p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p><strong>Should work consistently</strong></p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p><strong>I conducted a lot of research on possible solutions. No one product in the market fully solves the problem of printed books being inaccessible to the visually impaired. Here are some products that partially solve the problem.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p><strong>Screen Reader: This is an assistive technology that converts text and images to speech or braille. The reader needs to be loaded into the operating system. The reader can only scan for the text in the digital format and cannot scan for text in a non-digital format.</strong></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p><strong>Braille Display: This is another assistive technology that converts texts to braille. The display allows for texts to be read in braille one line at a time and costs over $2000. Another drawback is that the information needs to be preloaded in the format that the display can translate and display in braille.</strong></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p><strong>Braille Books: These are preprinted books in braille format. The drawback is the lack of availability of these books. Less than 1%of books are available in braille format.</strong></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>I used the above products as an inspiration to develop a solution that uses the strengths of each while minimizing the drawbacks. My solution uses a mini camera to convert the text in the physical format into a digital format. The camera is lightweight and can be affixed on any surface including eyeglasses. Once converted, the text is then translated into braille fonts. To display the braille fonts, I designed a custom braille display. The braille display connects with the camera either wired or wirelessly and displays the braille fonts. Unlike the braille display currently available in the market, my braille display solution uses sustainable miniature electromagnetic solenoids and innovative soft pneumatic actuators. These components need less electricity (less than 3v per cell) and make the product cost-effective, sustainable, and have a slim/small form factor.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n', '2022-02-19 06:54:46'),
