(157, 319, 228, '<p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Online Research </strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;I searched the following sites on the internet to see if my idea has already been implemented in some form or other:&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p><strong>Google Scholar</strong></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p><strong>IEEE</strong></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p><strong>Commercial websites: Amazon, eBay, etc&hellip;</strong></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p><strong>Research papers: ScienceDirect, Research Gate, Pubmed</strong></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p><strong>USPTO (patenting website)</strong></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Online Research results and analysis</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;I found a few similar inventions have been attempted. In the following list, I have selected a few of the most popular.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p><strong>Orbit reader 40</strong></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p><strong>OrCam read</strong></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p><strong>JAWS</strong></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>I analyzed and compared the solutions existing in the market against my criteria, giving them a score of 0-3, where&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p><strong>0 represents that it doesn&rsquo;t meet the criteria&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p><strong>3 represents that it fulfills the criteria. </strong></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>The graph below shows the rating scorecard for the existing products:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><img src=\"https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/O_-EzuDI2HDFtFqKA5cfSaoqynHX1vJDWfYHz4LaTSMNP7owGExpnK2rSiCp9AmXWM_4QT3RhwR5NWN4EV4XDBI6BMaPn8B9Md4_vG2RHrV9ETszLfMbANDxKg7i-A\" style=\"height:298px; width:706px\" /></strong></p>\r\n', '<p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;Expert Surveys:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>I reached out to several experts in the field who are professors, occupational therapists, low-vision specialists and interviewed them about challenges faced by the visually impaired when it comes to accessing printed reading materials, the methods or tools currently available in this space, and also got their feedback regarding how my invention would be helpful.&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Here are the experts I interviewed and surveyed about my invention:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p><strong>MSU - Resource Center for Persons with Disabilities</strong></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p><strong>Patty Obrzut at the Penrickton Center for Blind Children</strong></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p><strong>Christina Hedlich, Occupational Therapist/Low Vision Specialist at the Association for the Blind &amp; Visually Impaired</strong></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p><strong>Brent Perzentka, Certified Vision Rehabilitation Therapist at the Wisconsin Council of the Blind &amp; Visually Impaired</strong></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p><strong>Jim Denham, Access Technology Specialist at the Wisconsin Council of the Blind &amp; Visually Impaired</strong></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p><strong>Jennipher Wiebold, Department of Blindness &amp; Low Vision Studies at the Western Mich Univ.</strong></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n', '<p><strong>Research at Canton Public Library and personal interviews at Greater Detroit Agency for the Blind &amp; Visually Impaired</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>I visited my local library several times and read books and articles related to my invention. I read about challenges faced by the visually impaired, the tools and methods currently available in assistive technology, and their pros and cons.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>I also visited the &quot;Greater Detroit Agency for the Blind &amp; Visually Impaired&quot; and conducted personal interviews with people who were visually impaired to understand their daily challenges and experience with using assistive technology for reading.</strong></p>\r\n', '<p><strong>Teacher/Mentor Feedback</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>I have also been continuously working with my mentors Prof. Shiri Vivek and Mohammed Ahmed to get this input and feedback on my invention</strong></p>\r\n', '<p><strong>&nbsp;I found a few similar inventions have been attempted. In the following list, I have selected a few of the most popular.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p><strong>Orbit reader 40</strong></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p><strong>OrCam read</strong></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p><strong>JAWS</strong></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>I analyzed and compared the solutions existing in the market against my criteria, giving them a score of 0-3, where&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p><strong>0 represents that it doesn&rsquo;t meet the criteria&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p><strong>3 represents that it fulfills the criteria.&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>The graph below shows the rating scorecard for the existing products:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><img src=\"https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/O_-EzuDI2HDFtFqKA5cfSaoqynHX1vJDWfYHz4LaTSMNP7owGExpnK2rSiCp9AmXWM_4QT3RhwR5NWN4EV4XDBI6BMaPn8B9Md4_vG2RHrV9ETszLfMbANDxKg7i-A\" style=\"height:298px; width:706px\" /></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong><strong>I used the above products as an inspiration to develop a solution that uses the strengths of each while minimizing the drawbacks. My solution uses a mini camera to convert the text in the physical format into a digital format. The camera is lightweight and can be affixed on any surface including eyeglasses. Once converted, the text is then translated into braille fonts. To display the braille fonts, I designed a custom braille display. The braille display connects with the camera either wired or wirelessly and displays the braille fonts. Unlike the braille display currently available in the market, my braille display solution uses sustainable miniature electromagnetic solenoids and innovative soft pneumatic actuators. These components need less electricity (less than 3v per cell) and make the product cost-effective, sustainable, and have a slim/small form factor. &nbsp; </strong></p>\r\n', '2022-02-19 07:02:18'),
